2.caption: state and grid operators are grappling with a strange situation too much solar on sunny days when demand is not so high leads to negative electricity prices solar has many great benefits it costs almost nothing to operate after construction it creates no air pollution and it produces energy without burning fossil fuels but one major disadvantage is that the sun doesn t shine all the time more than 15 years ago researchers at the national renewable energy laboratory modeled the future of widespread solar power and found something strange when there is a lot of solar on the grid the gap between electricity demand and renewable energy becomes u shaped the morning spike in demand is replaced by almost zero demand at noon when solar can produce all the electricity people need then when the sun goes down demand spikes again california grid operator caiso calls this effect the duck curve the effect is most pronounced in the spring months when solar panels get a lot of sunlight but there is little demand for heating and cooling in recent years in california the duck curve has become a giant canyon and solar energy is not being used in 202 the state wasted 24 million megawatt hours of electricity 95 of which was solar last year the state experienced that level of waste in just the first 8 months of the year the state changed the system and now only compensates new solar owners for the value of their electricity to the grid in the spring when the duck curve is deepest the amount can drop to almost zero customers can get more money if they install panels and supply power to the grid in the morning or early evening this change has met with fierce opposition from californians and rooftop solar companies ps in europe for many years now negative electricity prices have been in place and you can buy electricity at an hourly rate choose when the price is low to use electricity and it is almost free
